zheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) dataset, the best accuracies, described as (mean ± standard deviation)%, among the three methods are (76.2 ± 11.3)% for AD vs. MCI, (94.8 ± 7.3)% for AD vs. HC, (76.5 ± 11.1)% for MCI vs. HC, and (71.0 ± 8.4)% for AD vs. MCI vs. HC, respectively. Integrative analysis of multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease prediction In this paper, we explore the effects of integrating multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease (AD) prediction using machine learning a... In this paper, we explore the effects of integrating multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease (AD) prediction using machine learning approaches. Precisely, we compare our three recent proposed feature selection methods (i.e. multiple kernel learning (MKL), high-order graph matching based feature selection (HGM-FS), sparse multimodal learning (SMML) using four widely-used modalities (i.e. magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET), cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), and genetic modality single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP)). This study demonstrates the performance of each method using these modalities individually or integratively, and may be valuable to clinical tests in practice.Our experimental results suggest that for AD prediction, in general, (1) in terms of accuracy, PET is the best modality; (2) Even though the discriminant power of genetic SNP features is weak, adding this modality to other modalities does help improve the classification accuracy; (3) HGM-FS works best among the three feature selection methods; (4) Some of the selected features are shared by all the feature selection methods, which may have high correlation with the disease. Using all the modalities on the Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) dataset, the best accuracies, described as (mean$\pm$standard deviation)%, among the three methods are (76.2$\pm$11.3)% for AD vs. MCI, (94.8$\pm$7.3)% for AD vs. HC, (76.5$\pm$11.1)% for MCI vs. HC, and (71.0$\pm$8.4)% for AD vs. MCI vs. HC, respectively. Frontiers | Integrative analysis of multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease prediction In this paper, we explore the effects of integrating multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease (AD) prediction using machine learning a... Frontiers | Integrative analysis of multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease prediction Quality and research integrity Institutional partnerships Frontiers Planet Prize Aging Neuroscience Archive Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias Cellular and Molecular Mechanisms of Brain-aging Neurocognitive Aging and Behavior Neuroinflammation and Neuropathy Parkinson’s Disease and Aging-related Movement Disorders Open access statement Contact editorial office Quality and research integrity Institutional partnerships Frontiers Planet Prize Aging Neuroscience Archive Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias Cellular and Molecular Mechanisms of Brain-aging Neurocognitive Aging and Behavior Neuroinflammation and Neuropathy Parkinson’s Disease and Aging-related Movement Disorders Open access statement Contact editorial office Aging Neuroscience Archive Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias Cellular and Molecular Mechanisms of Brain-aging Neurocognitive Aging and Behavior Neuroinflammation and Neuropathy Parkinson’s Disease and Aging-related Movement Disorders Open access statement Contact editorial office ORIGINAL RESEARCH article Front. Aging Neurosci. , 17 October 2014 Sec. Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias Volume 6 - 2014 | https://doi.org/10.3389/fnagi.2014.00260 Published in Frontiers in Aging Neuroscience Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias 4.5 impact factor 8.6 citescore Frontiers in Aging Neuroscience Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias Manuel Menéndez-González Central University Hospital of Asturias, Spain Harvard Medical School, United States Independent researcher, India 5. Discussion and conclusions 5. Discussion and conclusions Figure 1 View in article Figure 2 View in article Figure 3 View in article Table 1 View in article Table 2 View in article ORIGINAL RESEARCH article Front. Aging Neurosci. , 17 October 2014 Sec. Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias Volume 6 - 2014 | https://doi.org/10.3389/fnagi.2014.00260 Integrative analysis of multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease prediction D S Dinggang Shen 1,3 * T A The Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative The Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative 1. Department of Radiology and Biomedical Research Imaging Center, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill Chapel Hill, NC, USA 1. Department of Radiology and Biomedical Research Imaging Center, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill Chapel Hill, NC, USA 2. Department of Computer Science and Engineering, University of Texas at Arlington Arlington, TX, USA 2. Department of Computer Science and Engineering, University of Texas at Arlington Arlington, TX, USA 3. Department of Brain and Cognitive Engineering, Korea University Seoul, Republic of Korea 3. Department of Brain and Cognitive Engineering, Korea University Seoul, Republic of Korea In this paper, we explore the effects of integrating multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease (AD) prediction using machine learning approaches. Precisely, we compare our three recent proposed feature selection methods [i.e., multiple kernel learning (MKL), high-order graph matching based feature selection (HGM-FS), sparse multimodal learning (SMML)] using four widely-used modalities [i.e., magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET), cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), and genetic modality single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP)]. This study demonstrates the performance of each method using these modalities individually or integratively, and may be valuable to clinical tests in practice. Our experimental results suggest that for AD prediction, in general, (1) in terms of accuracy, PET is the best modality; (2) Even though the discriminant power of genetic SNP features is weak, adding this modality to other modalities does help improve the classification accuracy; (3) HGM-FS works best among the three feature selection methods; (4) Some of the selected features are shared by all the feature selection methods, which may have high correlation with the disease. Using all the modalities on the Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) dataset, the best accuracies, described as (mean ± standard deviation)%, among the three methods are (76.2 ± 11.3)% for AD vs. MCI, (94.8 ± 7.3)% for AD vs. HC, (76.5 ± 11.1)% for MCI vs. HC, and (71.0 ± 8.4)% for AD vs. MCI vs. HC, respectively. Alzheimer's disease (AD) is a complex chronically progressive neurodegenerative disease and the most common form of dementia in elderly people worldwide. As reported in Wimo et al. ( 1997 ), the Integrative analysis of multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease prediction In this paper, we explore the effects of integrating multi-dimensional imaging genomics data for Alzheimer's disease (AD) prediction using machine learning approaches. Precisely, we compare our three recent proposed feature selection methods [i.e., multiple kernel learning (MKL), high-order graph matching based feature selection (HGM-FS), sparse multimodal learning (SMML)] using four widely-used modalities [i.e., magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET), cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), and genetic modality single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP)]. This study demonstrates the performance of each method using these modalities individually or integratively, and may be valuable to clinical tests in practice. Our experimental results suggest that for AD prediction, in general, (1) in terms of accuracy, PET is the best modality; (2) Even though the discriminant power of genetic SN