camelyon,Multiple Instance Pathology Image Diagnosis Model based on Channel Attention and Data Augmentation,https://doi.org/10.1007/s42452-024-06093-9,openalex_camelyon_H_ml_top350.csv,https://openalex.org/W4401669251,2024,include_any_use,True,199820,html_plus_pdf,,Learned representation pipelines; Sequential predictive pipelines,2,0,1,0,1,0,,of the pathological WSI are feature extracted and dimension reduced using a pre-trained CNN model. This paper uses the contrastive learning framework SimCLR (A Simple Framework for Contrastive Learning of Visual Representations) [ 30 ] to pre-train the CNN model for feature extraction and encoding. SimCLR is an unsupe,,"model in this paper uses the whole pathological WSI as input and outputs the binary classification (negative, positive) prediction result for the WSI (Fig. 1 ). As shown in Fig. 1 , the entire model is divided into five parts, with the CA module and AUG data enhancement mechanism being the additional parts in the MIL model proposed in this paper. Fig. 1 The alternative text for this image may have been generated using tent. How does the channel attention module improve multiple instance learning? What are the effects of data augmentation on model performance in MIL? Similar content being viewed by others Calibration in Multiple Instance Learning: Evaluating Aggregation Methods for Ultrasound-Based Diagnosis Chapter © 2026 Cross-Scale Attention Guided Multi-instance Learning for Crohn’s Disease Diagnosis with Pathological Images Chapter © 2022 Robust Sensitivity Control in Digital Pathology via Tile Score Distribution Matching Chapter © 2026 Explore related subjects Discover the latest articles, books and news in related subjects, suggested using machine learning. Ca2+ imaging Disease Models Information Model Intelligence Augmentation Machine Learning Predictive medicine Deep Learning Applications in Digital Pathology 1 Introduction In clinical tumor diagnosis, pathological diagnosis is the ultimate means of confirming cancer and is considered the “gold standard” for tumor diagnosis. Traditionally, this process involves pathologists examining pathological tissue sections under a microscope. With the advent of Whole Slide Image (WSI) scanning, pathological images have been digitized, facilitating computer-aided tumor diagnosis and significantly advancing the field of digital pathology [ 1 ]. To maximize the preservation of the detailed features of pathological sections, pathological WSIs obtained by electron microscopy scanning are usually large in size (possibly exceeding 100,000 x 100,000 pixels). For pathological WSI data with local annotations (pixel-level or patch-level labels), classification or segmentation models can be trained using the local annotations of pathological WSIs [ 2 , 3 ]. However, these methods are not significantly different from mainstream image classification or segmentation tasks. In most cases, professional pathologists incur high costs when annotating large pathological WSI datasets. WSIs often lack pixel-level or patch-level local labels, and the large size of pathological WSI datasets with only image-level labels makes it impossible for common end-to-end CNN (Convolutional Neural Network) discriminative models to handle them directly. Multiple instance learning (MIL) [ 4 , 5 ] is a weakly supervised learning method that only requires the overall class label of a data bag (image) during the training process. The examples (image patches) in the data bag do not require class labels, making MIL very suitable for WSI classification applications without local annotations. Initial MIL methods were based on human-designed pooling operators, such as MAX-POOL, MEAN-POOL, and LSE (Log Sum Exp) pooling [ 6 ]. These methods do not contain trainable parameters and lack the ability to fit the data, resulting in poor performance on complex datasets. To address this issue, researchers have turned to study trainable MIL operators that leverage the powerful fitting ability of neural networks for pooling and feature extraction, thus eliminating the dependence on human priors. Global information-based methods include graph neural network-based MIL operators [ 7 ], capsule network-based MIL operators [ 8 , 9 ]. MILRNN models using recurrent neural networks (RNN) [ 10 ] that have achieved better classification results than traditional MIL pooling operators. The attention mechanism of neural networks can also guide the model to allocate computing resources to process more important information. Using additional mapping layers to calculate weights for features in specific dimensions and adaptively enhancing or suppressing specific features is a powerful way to address the problem of information overload. Inspired by the self-attention mechanism in the Transformer [ 11 ], Shao et al. [ 12 ] used a self-attention structure to calculate example weights and incorporated spatial feature information into the model, proposing the TransMIL (Transformer based MIL) model. Li B et al. [ 13 ] proposed the DSMIL method, which assigns weights to examples based on the relationships between them. This method first uses a fully connected network and max-pooling to obtain the most confident examples, then determines the similarity between examples using cosine similarity, weights all examples based on this similarity, and performs pooling. Finally, it combines the pooled result with the max-pooled result to jointly obtain the classification result. The ABMIL method proposed by Ilse et al. [ 14 ] is based on the attention mechanism, and Lu et al. [ 15 ] added a clustering mechanism as an additional constraint to the ABMIL model, proposing the CLAM (Clustering-constrained-attention Multiple-instance Learning) model. During the training process, pseudo labels of clustering are added to the examples with high weights. The CLAM-SB method adds two types of labels, while the CLAM-MB method adds multiple types of labels. These deep MIL models mentioned above all consider the relationship between examples, as the examples in the same image are sub-images at different positions, which are essentially different implementations of position attention mechanisms. From the perspective of neural network attention mechanisms, feature channel attention mechanisms can also bring significant efficiency improvements, such as the introduction of channel attention mechanisms in CNNs [ 16 ] leading to better performance. In the latest research, Hangchen Xiang et al. designed a multi-scale representation attention mechanism and embedded it into a two-branch deep network, improving the performance of MIL-based WSI classification [ 17 ]. This paper attempts to introduce feature channel attention mechanisms into current MIL models by adding an additional channel attention (Channel Attention, CA) mapping layer to calculate weights for features in the channel dimension, thereby achieving the effect of enhancing key features. Like most medical data deep learning tasks, deep learning models for pathological WSIs also face the problems of data scarcity and data imbalance (insufficient positive cases), which severely limit the generalization performance of deep learning models. Data augmentation is a data space solution proposed to alleviate data scarcity, usually increasing the number and diversity of data through transformations while ensuring the rationality of generated data to avoid degrading model performance. Common image transformation methods include geometric transformations (mirroring, rotation, and cropping, etc.) and color space transformations (color distortion, edge enhancement, and texture extraction, etc.). Taylor et al. [ 18 ] explored the effectiveness and comparison of these two enhancement methods. Zhang et al. [ 19 ] proposed the MIXUP method, which constructs new “virtual samples” by extracting two random samples from the training set and linearly interpolating them to train the learning model. Zhong Z et al. [ 20 ] used random elimination to enhance image data samples. DeVries et al. [ 21 ] proposed Cutout regularization to enhance data. Generative adversarial Networks (GANs) have also been applied to data augmentation, with Frid-Adar et al. [ 22 ] using DCGANs [ 23 ] to generate medical images of liver lesions. In addition, there are data augmentation methods developed based on the meta-learning concept in Neural Architecture Search (NAS) [ 24 , 25 , 26 ]. Pei Liu et al. proposed a novel Pseudo-bag Mixup (PseMix) data augmentation scheme based on the idea of Mixup, aiming to improve the training of MIL models [ 27 ]. Due to the lack of example labels in MIL tasks, the above methods cannot be directly applied to MIL tasks, and if data augmentation is solely performed on examples, the improvement of bag feature generalization is limited, so it is necessary to construct a bag enhancement method. Li Z et al. [ 28 ] proposed a MIL data augmentation method applied to a COVID-19 lung CT image dataset. They regarded high-weight examples in positive bags as positive examples and low-weight examples as negative examples, and then randomly extracted positive and negative examples to combine and generate new virtual positive bags, thus achieving the purpose of data augmentation. Through the analysis of experimental results of major MIL models, it was found that the current MIL model has a high false negative error rate (low sensitivity), mainly due to the small proportion of positive pathological regions in most positive pathological WSIs, leading to a low sensitivity of the trained network. False negative diagnosis can delay the treatment of serious diseases, miss the best treatment opportunity, and, reducing false negatives is very important for clinical applicability. Although Li Z et al., [ 28 ] their data augmentation method is generally effective, there is a situation where virtual positive bags are constructed using examples from positive bags that the model itself cannot correctly recognize, so it cannot effectively reduce false negatives. Hu et al. [ 29 ] proposed that in image fine-grained classification, by cropping partial areas of objects in images, the network can be encouraged to focus on multiple distinguishable features instead of just a few features. Drawing on this idea, this paper proposes an AUG bag enhancement mechanism for MIL models of pathological images, which extracts high-weight positive examples that can be identified in positive bags and randomly deletes high-weight examples. This mechanism encourages MIL models to extract features from multiple high-weight examples, thus achieving the expected effect of effectively reducing false negatives. To verify the performance of the proposed method, we added the CA mechanism to recent MIL models and adopted the AUG data enhancement mechanism during model training. Experiments were conducted on public pathological WSI datasets CAMELYON16 and CAMELYON17. The experimental results comparing the classification performance of several MIL models before and after adding CA and AUG mechanisms show that both mechanisms can effectively improve the performance of MIL models. 2 Model structure The proposed optimization model in this paper uses the whole pathological WSI as input and outputs the binary classification (negative, positive) prediction result for the WSI (Fig. 1 ). As shown in Fig. 1 , the entire model is divided into five parts, with the CA module and AUG data enhancement mechanism being the additional parts in the MIL model proposed in this paper. Fig. 1 The alternative text for this image may have been generated using AI. Full size image Overall model structure Data preprocessing: After removing the background area from the pathological WSI (wh agnosis with Pathological Images Chapter © 2022 Robust Sensitivity Control in Digital Pathology via Tile Score Distribution Matching Chapter © 2026 Explore related subjects Discover the latest articles, books and news in related subjects, suggested using machine learning. Ca2+ imaging Disease Models Information Model Intelligence Augmentation Machine Learning Predictive medicine Deep Learning Applications in Digital Pathology 1 Introduction In clinical tumor diagnosis, pathological diagnosis is the ultimate means of confirming cancer and is considered the “gold standard” for tumor diagnosis. Traditionally, this process involves pathologists examining pathological tissue sections under a microscope. With the advent of Whole Slide Image (WSI) scanning, pathological images have been digitized, facilitating computer-aided tumor diagnosis and significantly advancing the field of digital pathology [ 1 ]. To maximize the preservation of the detailed features of pathological sections, pathological WSIs obtained by electron microscopy scanning are usually large in size (possibly exceeding 100,000 x 100,000 pixels). For pathological WSI data with local annotations (pixel-level or patch-level labels), classification or segmentation models can be trained using the local annotations of pathological WSIs [ 2 , 3 ]. However, these methods are not significantly different from mainstream image classification or segmentation tasks. In most cases, professional pathologists incur high costs when annotating large pathological WSI datasets. WSIs often lack pixel-level or patch-level local labels, and the large size of pathological WSI datasets with only image-level labels makes it impossible for common end-to-end CNN (Convolutional Neural Network) discriminative models to handle them directly. Multiple instance learning (MIL) [ 4 , 5 ] is a weakly supervised learning method that only requires the overall class label of a data bag (image) during the training process. The examples (image patches) in the data bag do not require class labels, making MIL very suitable for WSI classification applications without local annotations. Initial MIL methods were based on human-designed pooling operators, such as MAX-POOL, MEAN-POOL, and LSE (Log Sum Exp) pooling [ 6 ]. These methods do not contain trainable parameters and lack the ability to fit the data, resulting in poor performance on complex datasets. To address this issue, researchers have turned to study trainable MIL operators that leverage the powerful fitting ability of neural networks for pooling and feature extraction, thus eliminating the dependence on human priors. Global information-based methods include graph neural network-based MIL operators [ 7 ], capsule network-based MIL operators [ 8 , 9 ]. MILRNN models using recurrent neural networks (RNN) [ 10 ] that have achieved better classification results than traditional MIL pooling operators. The attention mechanism of neural networks can also guide the model to allocate computing resources to process more important information. Using additional mapping layers to calculate weights for features in specific dimensions and adaptively enhancing or suppressing specific features is a powerful way to address the problem of information overload. Inspired by the self-attention mechanism in the Transformer [ 11 ], Shao et al. [ 12 ] used a self-attention structure to calculate example weights and incorporated spatial feature information into the model, proposing the TransMIL (Transformer based MIL) model. Li B et al. [ 13 ] proposed the DSMIL method, which assigns weights to examples based on the relationships between them. This method first uses a fully connected network and max-pooling to obtain the most confident examples, then determines the similarity between examples using cosine similarity, weights all examples based on this similarity, and performs pooling. Finally, it combines the pooled result with the max-pooled result to jointly obtain the classification result. The ABMIL method proposed by Ilse et al. [ 14 ] is based on the attention mechanism, and Lu et al. [ 15 ] added a clustering mechanism as an additional constraint to the ABMIL model, proposing the CLAM (Clustering-constrained-attention Multiple-instance Learning) model. During the training process, pseudo labels of clustering are added to the examples with high weights. The CLAM-SB method adds two types of labels, while the CLAM-MB method adds multiple types of labels. These deep MIL models mentioned above all consider the relationship between examples, as the examples in the same image are sub-images at different positions, which are essentially different implementations of position attention mechanisms. From the perspective of neural network attention mechanisms, feature channel attention mechanisms can also bring significant efficiency improvements, such as the introduction of channel attention mechanisms in CNNs [ 16 ] leading to better performance. In the latest research, Hangchen Xiang et al. designed a multi-scale representation attention mechanism and embedded it into a two-branch deep network, improving the performance of MIL-based WSI classification [ 17 ]. This paper attempts to introduce feature channel attention mechanisms into current MIL models by adding an additional channel attention (Channel Attention, CA) mapping layer to calculate weights for features in the channel dimension, thereby achieving the effect of enhancing key features. Like most medical data deep learning tasks, deep learning models for pathological WSIs also face the problems of data scarcity and data imbalance (insufficient positive cases), which severely limit the generalization performance of deep learning models. Data augmentation is a data space solution proposed to alleviate data scarcity, usually increasing the number and diversity of data through transformations while ensuring the rationality of generated data to avoid degrading model performance. Common image transformation methods include geometric transformations (mirroring, rotation, and cropping, etc.) and color space transformations (color distortion, edge enhancement, and texture extraction, etc.). Taylor et al. [ 18 ] explored the effectiveness and comparison of these two enhancement methods. Zhang et al. [ 19 ] proposed the MIXUP method, which constructs new “virtual samples” by extracting two random samples from the training set and linearly interpolating them to train the learning model. Zhong Z et al. [ 20 ] used random elimination to enhance image data samples. DeVries et al. [ 21 ] proposed Cutout regularization to enhance data. Generative adversarial Networks (GANs) have also been applied to data augmentation, with Frid-Adar et al. [ 22 ] using DCGANs [ 23 ] to generate medical images of liver lesions. In addition, there are data augmentation methods developed based on the meta-learning concept in Neural Architecture Search (NAS) [ 24 , 25 , 26 ]. Pei Liu et al. proposed a novel Pseudo-bag Mixup (PseMix) data augmentation scheme based on the idea of Mixup, aiming to improve the training of MIL models [ 27 ]. Due to the lack of example labels in MIL tasks, the above methods cannot be directly applied to MIL tasks, and if data augmentation is solely performed on examples, the improvement of bag feature generalization is limited, so it is necessary to construct a bag enhancement method. Li Z et al. [ 28 ] proposed a MIL data augmentation method applied to a COVID-19 lung CT image dataset. They regarded high-weight examples in positive bags as positive examples and low-weight examples as negative examples, and then randomly extracted positive and negative examples to combine and generate new virtual positive bags, thus achieving the purpose of data augmentation. Through the analysis of experimental results of major MIL models, it was found that the current MIL model has a high false negative error rate (low sensitivity), mainly due to the small proportion of positive pathological regions in most positive pathological WSIs, leading to a low sensitivity of the trained network. False negative diagnosis can delay the treatment of serious diseases, miss the best treatment opportunity, and, reducing false negatives is very important for clinical applicability. Although Li Z et al., [ 28 ] their data augmentation method is generally effective, there is a situation where virtual positive bags are constructed using examples from positive bags that the model itself cannot correctly recognize, so it cannot effectively reduce false negatives. Hu et al. [ 29 ] proposed that in image fine-grained classification, by cropping partial areas of objects in images, the network can be encouraged to focus on multiple distinguishable features instead of just a few features. Drawing on this idea, this paper proposes an AUG bag enhancement mechanism for MIL models of pathological images, which extracts high-weight positive examples that can be identified in positive bags and randomly deletes high-weight examples. This mechanism encourages MIL models to extract features from multiple high-weight examples, thus achieving the expected effect of effectively reducing false negatives. To verify the performance of the proposed method, we added the CA mechanism to recent MIL models and adopted the AUG data enhancement mechanism during model training. Experiments were conducted on public pathological WSI datasets CAMELYON16 and CAMELYON17. The experimental results comparing the classification performance of several MIL models before and after adding CA and AUG mechanisms show that both mechanisms can effectively improve the performance of MIL models. 2 Model structure The proposed optimization model in this paper uses the whole pathological WSI as input and outputs the binary classification (negative, positive) prediction result for the WSI (Fig. 1 ). As shown in Fig. 1 , the entire model is divided into five parts, with the CA module and AUG data enhancement mechanism being the additional parts in the MIL model proposed in this paper. Fig. 1 The alternative text for this image may have been generated using AI. Full size image Overall model structure Data preprocessing: After removin