amework for Contrastive Learning of Visual Representations) [ 30 ] to pre-train the CNN model for feature extraction and encoding. SimCLR is an unsupervised image feature extraction framework (Fig. 2 ), which uses a contrastive learning strategy to train the feature extraction network \(f(\bullet )\) and the mapping network \(g(\bullet )\) . The training goal is to enable the model \(p(\bullet )\) , combined from \(f(\bullet )\) and \(g(\bullet )\) , to discern the similarity between two images. During training, SimCLR selects an image x from the data image set \(\{\widetilde{x_k}\}\) and generates its transformed image \(\widetilde{x_i}\) and \(\widetilde{x_j}\) , while removing image x from the image set \(\{\widetilde{x_k}\}\) . Subsequently, the image set \(\{\widetilde{x_k}\}\) , \(\widetilde{x_i}\) and \(\widetilde{x_j}\) are input into the network \(p(\bullet )\) to obtain the results \(p(\{\widetilde{x_k}\})\) , \(p(\widetilde{x_i})\) and \(p(\widetilde{x_j})\) . The training objective is to make the spatial metric distance between \(p(\widetilde{x_i})\) and \(p(\widetilde{x_j})\) closer relative to the spatial metric distance between \(p(\widetilde{x_i})\) and \(p(\{\widetilde{x_k}\})\) . The SimCLR calculates the difference between the model output and the actual situation based on the contrastive loss ( 1 ): $$\begin{aligned} L(Z_i,Z_j)=-log\frac{e^{sim(Z_i,Z_j)}}{\sum _{k}I_{[k\ne i]}e^{sim(Z_i,Z_j)}} \end{aligned}$$ (1) where \(sim(u,v)=u^{T}v/\left\| u\right\| \left\| v\right\|\) , \(I_{[k\ne i]}\in \{0,1\}\) is an indicator function, 1 when \(k\ne i\) , and 0 when \(k = i\) . After training, the feature extraction network \(f(\bullet )\) will serve as the feature extractor of the MIL model, while the mapping network \(g(\bullet )\) is discarded. The off-line trained unsupervised image encoder \(f(\bullet )\) maps \(X_n\) to an L-dimensional vector \(h_n\) , i.e., \(X=\{X_1,X_2,\cdots ,X_n,\cdots ,X_N\}\rightarrow \{h_1,h_2,\cdots ,h_n,\cdots ,h_N\}\) , \(h_n\in R^{1\times L}\) . Fig. 2 The alternative text for this image may have been generated using AI. Full size image SimCLR task CA module: The feature-encoded data enters the CA module, which maps the example features in the channel dimension and weights the example features based on the mapping results. MIL model: The output of the CA module is fed into the MIL model to obtain the class discrimination result Class \(\widehat{Y}\) , where the MIL model in Fig. 1 can be replaced with various MIL algorithms. In this paper, we focus on using three MIL models recently published: ABMIL, CLAM-SB, and CLAM-MB for experiments. AUG: A data enhancement mechanism that balances positive and negative data bags during the joint training of the CA and MIL models and randomly deletes high-weight examples to generate virtual positive bags. 3 Channel attention (CA) The attention mechanism in neural networks can adjust the weights of different parts of input features, allowing the model to focus on important features. In recent years, pathological MIL diagnosis models have focused on the relationship betwe on the relationships between them. This method first uses a fully connected network and max-pooling to obtain the most confident examples, then determines the similarity between examples using cosine similarity, weights all examples based on this similarity, and performs pooling. Finally, it combines the pooled result with the max-pooled result to jointly obtain the classification result. The ABMIL method proposed by Ilse et al. [ 14 ] is based on the attention mechanism, and Lu et al. [ 15 ] added a clustering mechanism as an additional constraint to the ABMIL model, proposing the CLAM (Clustering-constrained-attention Multiple-instance Learning) model. During the training process, pseudo labels of clustering are added to the examples with high weights. The CLAM-SB method adds two types of labels, while the CLAM-MB method adds multiple types of labels. These deep MIL models m