camelyon,A Mixture-of-Experts Decision Support System for Digital Pathology,https://doi.org/10.24251/hicss.2025.390,openalex_camelyon_H_ml_top350.csv,https://openalex.org/W4407208669,2025,include_any_use,True,35580,html_plus_pdf,,Learned representation pipelines; Fusion-centric architectures; Sequential predictive pipelines,3,0,1,1,1,0,,"nto a single model by introducing a MoE projection to aggregate knowledge from various tasks and to produce the initial feature embedding. The initial feature embedding is processed by the visual encoder, built based upon Transformers, to extract the representative and useful information for classification. The resu","erging task-specific models, our approach can be considered an ensemble model. Recent ensemble methods tend to focus on late fusion ofmultiple predictions to improve performance on a single target task (Dong et al., 2020; Yang et al., 2023). Our system, however, introduces a learnable MoE projection to generat","final classification. There are two common aggregation methods. The first is instance-level aggregation, which makes a prediction per patch and aggregates all the predictions for final decision-making (Campanella et al., 2019; Hou et al., 2016). The second is bag embedding-level aggregation. This approach combines patch embeddings via attention mechanisms, producing a bag embedding, and makes the final decision based on the bag embedding (Campanella et al., 2019; Ilse et al., 2018; Lu et al., 2021; Shao et al., 2021; H. Zhang et al., 2022). As these methods are used, it is often evaluated on a single classification task; for instance, provided with two tasks/datasets such as breast cancer sub-typing and kidney cancer sub-typing, one develops two models, one for each task. Though this approach can handle the two tasks, one model cannot leverage data/knowledge from the other task to enrich the model’s Proceedings of the 58th Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences | 2025 Page 3228URI: https://hdl.handle.net/10125/109232 978-0-9981331-8-8 (CC BY-NC-ND 4.0) ability. As the number of available datasets and tasks continues to grow, it becomes obvious that developing a separate, designated model for each task can neither fully utilize the datasets nor advance the generalization ability of the model. Therefore, an alternative method is needed to fully utilize the existing data/knowledge and to improve the capability of the models in supporting decision making in clinics. In this study, we propose a mixture-of-experts (MoE) decision support system for WSI classification. MoE techniques have shown to be effective in several vision tasks such as semantic segmentation, human parsing, and object boundary detection (Chen et al., 2023; Ye & Xu, 2023). For instance, Ye and Xu (2023) proposed to decompose the feature maps into a set of multiple representative features that are processed by an expert as an MLP. A gating mechanism is employed to determine how much an expert contributes to a task. Chen et al. (2023) introduces a sparse MoE layer to replace the normal MLP layer in the Vision Transformer (ViT) (Dosovitskiy et al., 2020). A router network and multiple MLP experts are introduced for each task. The router decides the number of experts to use and their contribution to generating the task-specific token sequence. Inspired by these studies, we adopt MoE techniques to combine multiple existing models of which each can conduct a specific task in pathology, and to form group intelligence that can improve the overall classification performance. To achieve this, we employ multiple pathology classification tasks and train a separate model for each WSI classification task. Then, we merge the individual models to further improve the classification performance. Since each model is trained on a particular classification task, we assume that the model possesses proper knowledge of the given task, i.e., an expert of the task. By combining these models, i.e., opinions of different experts, we aim to advance the overall classification performance. We construct the proposed MoE decision support system as a generative Transformer-based model, which consists of a MoE projection layer, a visual encoder, and a language decoder. We merge multiple individual models trained on specific tasks into a single model by introducing a MoE projection to aggregate knowledge from various tasks and to produce the initial feature embedding. The initial feature embedding is processed by the visual encoder, built based upon Transformers, to extract the representative and useful information for classification. The resultant feature embedding is fed into the language decoder to make the final decision. By merging task-specific models, our approach can be considered an ensemble model. Recent ensemble methods tend to focus on late fusion ofmultiple predictions to improve performance on a single target task (Dong et al., 2020; Yang et al., 2023). Our system, however, introduces a learnable MoE projection to generate feature embeddings for a shared unified model. This design allows a single core model to handle multiple classification tasks, thereby enhancing the generalization ability of the model and achieving superior performance compared to the conventional approach of using individual models for each task. Furthermore, different from the conventional computational models, the proposed system leverages the power of language models to enable flexible classification that performs well across multiple WSI classification tasks by formulating the prediction step as auto-regressive decoding, in which the next output is conditioned on the previous output. In recent studies, the language decoder has been proven to have the ability to learn the correspondence between textual diagnostic terms/labels and pathology images to facilitate better classification performance (Nguyen & Kwak, 2023; R. Zhang et al., 2020). However, the ability to leverage this for WSIs has not been investigated yet. We evaluate the proposed system using five WSI classification tasks and show that the proposed system, in general, outperforms the individual models. In summary, our contribution is listed as below: • We introduce a mixture-of-experts (MoE) decision support system, which is built based upon a generative Transformers in an encoder-decoder architecture with an auto-regressive decoding process that can handle multiple WSI classification tasks. • We introduce a MoE technique as a projection layer, which produces useful and informative embeddings that can aggregate knowledge from multiple tasks. • The proposed system outperforms individually trained models, facilitating improved decision making in clinics. The remainder of this paper is structured as follows: Section 2 presents the proposed approach in detail. Section 3 reports the classification results and ablation studies. Section 4 concludes the study, summarizes the findings, and suggests future directions. 2. Methodology 2.1. Problem definition Suppose that we are given Tmodels. Each model is denoted as F(·, θt)and is trained specifically for the Page 3229 Figure 1: Overview of the Mixture-of-Experts Transformer-based model for generalizable WSI classification. The figure illustrates the overview of the Transformer-based architecture and the model merging stage. Given T task-specific models, in the model merging stage, only a router R(·)andThead classifiers are trained. τtdenotes the task vector for the tthtask, which is frozen during the model merging stage. P(·)denotes the projection layer which projects the bag of patch features into the model space. tthWSI classification task. We attempt to merge these Tmodels into one unified model, F(·, θmerge ), that can improve the performance of each individual tthmodel. Given a WSI Xfrom any task, the unified model is expected to predict the outcome ˆY=F(X, θmerge ), where ˆYis the predicted diagnostic term. 2.2. Pre-processing WSI processing. Given a WSI X, a patch sampling procedure is adopted to tile Xinto a bag of patches. In this process, tissue regions on Xare segmented and the patches from the tissue regions are cropped to form a bag of patches. Then, an off-the-shelf pre-trained feature extractor G(·)is utilized to obtain a bag of patch feature embeddings x={xi}N i=1, where xi∈Rdfanddfis the dimension of the feature embedding, which is dependent onG(·). Vocabulary. The proposed system predicts the textual diagnostic term by using the auto-regressive decoding. The auto-regressive decoding requires a vocabulary of the textual diagnostic terms. We build the vocabulary as follows. Given that the tthtask has ntdiagnostic categories Ct={ct i}nt i=1, we map each category ct ito the natural term St i. The term St iis then tokenized into nt iwords, i.e.,St i={st j}nt i j=1. Then, for each tthtask, we form the tthvoc ty Seoul, Republic of Korea, 02841 {doanhbc, jkwak }@korea.ac.kr Abstract Whole slide image (WSI) classification is a core task in digital pathology that can assist decision-making procedures for pathologists. Several models, mainly built based upon multiple-instance learning, have shown to be effective in processing and analyzing WSIs. However, these are designed, trained, and evaluated on a single classification task, and thus the models are limited to a specific task and cannot utilize the data and knowledge from other tasks. This substantially limits the ability and expandability of the model to support clinical decision-making. In this study, we present a mixture-of-experts decision support system for digital pathology. The proposed decision support system merges multiple individual models, of which each is tailored to a specific task, and forms a unified model equipped with group intelligence that can handle multiple classification tasks. The proposed system utilizes Transformer architecture to process WSIs and a language decoder to enable flexible classification across multiple tasks. The experiments were conducted on five datasets: CAMELYON16, TCGA–BRCA, TCGA–NSCLC, TCGA–RCC, and TCGA–ESCA, achieving accuracies of 96.124%, 95.062%, 90.805%, 95.402%, and 91.071%, and F1 of 0.965, 0.971, 0.908, 0.711, and 0.918, respectively. These results demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed approach in supporting clinical decision-making. Keywords: whole slide image, classification, cancer sub-typing, mixture-of-experts 1. Introduction Digital pathology represents a fundamental transformation and revolution of the practice ofpathology, which involves the transition from glass slides to digitized virtual slides, from manual to automated management and preparation, from subjective to objective measurements and decision making, etc. The core of digital pathology can be two-fold. One is whole slide imaging (WSI), which denotes a high-resolution (e.g., 20×or40× magnification) digitized image of an entire glass slide, capturing organs/tissues in gigapixel details (Li et al., 2022). The other is advanced computational techniques such as deep neural networks that can analyze WSIs and can support the decision making on them. Nowadays, WSIs are widely available due to the rapid adoption of digital scanners, and the development of computational techniques is continuously advancing. Recent studies have focused on multiple-instance learning (MIL) for WSI analysis. MIL methods consider a WSI as a bag of patches, learn to capture patterns in the bag/patch, and aggregate them for final classification. There are two common aggregation methods. The first is instance-level aggregation, which makes a prediction per patch and aggregates all the predictions for final decision-making (Campanella et al., 2019; Hou et al., 2016). The second is bag embedding-level aggregation. This approach combines patch embeddings via attention mechanisms, producing a bag embedding, and makes the final decision based on the bag embedding (Campanella et al., 2019; Ilse et al., 2018; Lu et al., 2021; Shao et al., 2021; H. Zhang et al., 2022). As these methods are used, it is often evaluated on a single classification task; for instance, provided with two tasks/datasets such as breast cancer sub-typing and kidney cancer sub-typing, one develops two models, one for each task. Though this approach can handle the two tasks, one model cannot leverage data/knowledge from the other task to enrich the model’s Proceedings of the 58th Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences | 2025 Page 3228URI: https://hdl.handle.net/10125/109232 978-0-9981331-8-8 (CC BY-NC-ND 4.0) ability. As the number of available datasets and tasks continues to grow, it becomes obvious that developing a separate, designated model for each task can neither fully utilize the datasets nor advance the generalization ability of the model. Therefore, an alternative method is needed to fully utilize the existing data/knowledge and to improve the capability of the models in supporting decision making in clinics. In this study, we propose a mixture-of-experts (MoE) decision support system for WSI classification. MoE techniques have shown to be effective in several vision tasks such as semantic segmentation, human parsing, and object boundary detection (Chen et al., 2023; Ye & Xu, 2023). For instance, Ye and Xu (2023) proposed to decompose the feature maps into a set of multiple representative features that are processed by an expert as an MLP. A gating mechanism is employed to determine how much an expert contributes to a task. Chen et al. (2023) introduces a sparse MoE layer to replace the normal MLP layer in the Vision Transformer (ViT) (Dosovitskiy et al., 2020). A router network and multiple MLP experts are introduced for each task. The router decides the number of experts to use and their contribution to generating the task-specific token sequence. Inspired by these studies, we adopt MoE techniques to combine multiple existing models of which each can conduct a specific task in pathology, and to form group intelligence that can improve the overall classification performance. To achieve this, we employ multiple pathology classification tasks and train a separate model for each WSI classification task. Then, we merge the individual models to further improve the classification performance. Since each model is trained on a particular classification task, we assume that the model possesses proper knowledge of the given task, i.e., an expert of the task. By combining these models, i.e., opinions of different experts, we aim to advance the overall classification performance. We construct the proposed MoE decision support system as a generative Transformer-based model, which consists of a MoE projection layer, a visual encoder, and a language decoder. We merge multiple individual models trained on specific tasks into a single model by introducing a MoE projection to aggregate knowledge from various tasks and to produce the initial feature embedding. The initial feature embedding is processed by the visual encoder, built based upon Transformers, to extract the representative and useful information for classification. The resultant feature embedding is fed into the language decoder to make the final decision. By merging task-specific models, our approach can be considered an ensemble model. Recent ensemble methods tend to focus on late fusion ofmultiple predictions to improve performance on a single target task (Dong et al., 2020; Yang et al., 2023). Our system, however, introduces a learnable MoE projection to generate feature embeddings for a shared unified model. This design allows a single core model to handle multiple classification tasks, thereby enhancing the generalization ability of the model and achieving superior performance compared to the conventional approach of using individual models for each task. Furthermore, different from the conventional computational models, the proposed system leverages the power of language models to enable flexible classification that performs well across multiple WSI classification tasks by formulating the prediction step as auto-regressive decoding, in which the next output is conditioned on the previous output. In recent studies, the language decoder has been proven to have the ability to learn the correspondence between textual diagnostic terms/labels and pathology images to facilitate better classification performance (Nguyen & Kwak, 2023; R. Zhang et al., 2020). However, the ability to leverage this for WSIs has not been investigated yet. We evaluate the proposed system using five WSI classification tasks and show that the proposed system, in general, outperforms the individual models. In summary, our contribution is listed as below: • We introduce a mixture-of-experts (MoE) decision support system, which is built based upon a generative Transformers in an encoder-decoder architecture with an auto-regressive decoding process that can handle multiple WSI classification tasks. • We introduce a MoE technique as a projection layer, which produces useful and informative embeddings that can aggregate knowledge from multiple tasks. • The proposed system outperforms individually trained models, facilitating improved decision making in clinics. The remainder of this paper is structured as follows: Section 2 presents the proposed approach in detail. Section 3 reports the classification results and ablation studies. Section 4 concludes the study, summarizes the findings, and suggests future directions. 2. Methodology 2.1. Problem definition Suppose that we are given Tmodels. Each model is denoted as F(·, θt)and is trained specifically for the Page 3229 Figure 1: Overview of the Mixture-of-Experts Transformer-based model for generalizable WSI classification. The figure illustrates the overview of the Transformer-based architecture and the model merging stage. Given T task-specific models, in the model merging stage, only a router R(·)andThead classifiers are trained. τtdenotes the task vector for the tthtask, which is frozen during the model merging stage. P(·)denotes the projection layer which projects the bag of patch features into the model space. tthWSI classification task. We attempt to merge these Tmodels into one unified model, F(·, θmerge ), that can improve the performance of each individual tthmodel. Given a WSI Xfrom any task, the unified model is expected to predict the outcome ˆY=F(X, θmerge ), where ˆYis the predicted diagnostic term. 2.2. Pre-processing WSI processing. Given a WSI X, a patch sampling procedure is adopted to tile Xinto a bag of patches. In this process, tissue regions on Xare segmented and the patches from the tissue regions are cropped to form a bag of patches. Then, an off-the-shelf pre-trained feature extractor G(·)is utilized to obtain a bag of patch feature embeddings x={xi}N i=1, where xi∈Rdfanddfis the dimension of the feature embedding, which is dependent onG(·). Vocabulary. The proposed system predicts the textual diagnostic term by using the auto-regressive decoding. The auto-regressive decoding requires a vocabulary of the textual diagnostic terms. We build the vocabulary as follows. Given that the tthtask has ntdiagnostic categories Ct={ct i}nt i=1, we map each category ct ito the natural term St i. The term St iis then tokenized into nt iwords, i.e.,St i={st j}nt i j=1. Then, for each tthtask, we form the tthvocabulary Vt={st j}nt voc j=1where nt voc= Pnt i=1nt iwords. Overall, for Ttasks, the vocabularybecomes V={si}nvoc i=1where nvoc=PT t=1nt voc. 2.3. Transformer-based en a and knowledge from other tasks. This substantially limits the ability and expandability of the model to support clinical decision-making. In this study, we present a mixture-of-experts decision support system for digital pathology. The proposed decision support system merges multiple individual models, of which each is tailored to a specific task, and forms a unified model equipped with group intelligence that can handle multiple classification tasks. The proposed system utilizes Transformer architecture to process WSIs and a language decoder to enable flexible classification across multiple tasks. The experiments were conducted on five datasets: CAMELYON16, TCGA–BRCA, TCGA–NSCLC, TCGA–RCC, and TCGA–ESCA, achieving accuracies of 96.124%, 95.062%, 90.805%, 95.402%, and 91.071%, and F1 of 0.965, 0.971, 0.908, 0.711, and 0.918, respectively. These results demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed approach in supporting clinical decision-making. Keywords: whole slide image, classification, cancer sub-typing, mixture-of-experts 1. Introduction Digital pathology represents a fundamental transformation and revolution of the practice ofpathology, which involves the transition from glass slides to digitized virtual slides, from manual to automated management and preparation, from subjective to objective measurements and decision making, etc. The core of digital pathology can be two-fold. One is whole slide imaging (WSI), which denotes a high-resolution (e.g., 20×or40× magnification) digitized image of an entire glass slide, capturing organs/tissues in gigapixel details (Li et al., 2022). The other is advanced computational techniques such as deep neural networks that can analyze WSIs and can support the decision making on them. Nowadays, WSIs are widely available due to the rapid adoption of digital scanners, and the development of computational techniques is continuously advancing. Recent studies have focused on multiple-instance learning (MIL) for WSI analysis. MIL methods consider a WSI as a bag of patches, learn to capture patterns in the bag/patch, and aggregate them for final classification. There are two common aggregation methods. The first is instance-level aggregation, which makes a prediction per patch and aggregates all the predictions for final decision-making (Campanella et al., 2019; Hou et al., 2016). The second is bag embedding-level aggregation. This approach combines patch embeddings via attentio