 sequence. Inspired by these studies, we adopt MoE techniques to combine multiple existing models of which each can conduct a specific task in pathology, and to form group intelligence that can improve the overall classification performance. To achieve this, we employ multiple pathology classification tasks and train a separate model for each WSI classification task. Then, we merge the individual models to further improve the classification performance. Since each model is trained on a particular classification task, we assume that the model possesses proper knowledge of the given task, i.e., an expert of the task. By combining these models, i.e., opinions of different experts, we aim to advance the overall classification performance. We construct the proposed MoE decision support system as a generative Transformer-based model, which consists of a MoE projection layer, a visual encoder, and a language decoder. We merge multiple individual models trained on specific tasks into a single model by introducing a MoE projection to aggregate knowledge from various tasks and to produce the initial feature embedding. The initial feature embedding is processed by the visual encoder, built based upon Transformers, to extract the representative and useful information for classification. The resultant feature embedding is fed into the language decoder to make the final decision. By merging task-specific models, our approach can be considered an ensemble model. Recent ensemble methods tend to focus on late fusion ofmultiple predictions to improve performance on a single target task (Dong et al., 2020; Yang et al., 2023). Our system, however, introduces a learnable MoE projection to generate feature embeddings for a shared unified model. This design allows a single core model to handle multiple classification tasks, thereby enhancing the generalization ability of the model and achieving superior performance compared to the conventional approach of using individual models for each task. Furthermore, different from the conventional computational models, the proposed system leverages the power of language models to enable flexible classification that performs well across multiple WSI classification tasks by formulating the prediction step as auto-regressive decoding, in which the next output is conditioned on the previous output. In recent studies, the language decoder has been proven to have the ability to learn the correspondence between textual diagnostic terms/labels and pathology images to facilitate better classification performance (Nguyen & Kwak, 2023; R. Zhang et al., 2020). However, the ability to leverage this for WSIs has not been investigated yet. We evaluate the proposed system using five WSI classification tasks and show that the proposed system, in general, outperforms the individual models. In summary, our contribution is listed as below: • We introduce a mixture-of-experts (MoE) decision support system, which is built based upon a generative Transformers in an encoder-decoder architecture with an auto-regressive decoding process that can handle multiple WSI classification tasks. • We introduce a MoE technique as a projection layer, which produces useful and informative embeddings that can aggregate knowledge from multiple tasks. • The proposed system outperforms individually trained models, facilitating improved decision making in clinics. The remainder of this paper is structured as follows: Section 2 presents the proposed approach in detail. Section 3 reports the classification results and ablation studies. Section 4 concludes the study, summarizes the findings, and suggests future directions. 2. Methodology 2.1. Problem definition Suppose that we are given Tmodels. Each model is denoted as F(·, θt)and is trained specifically for the Page 3229 Figure 1: Overview of the Mixture-of-Experts Transformer-based model for generalizable WSI classification. The figure illustrates the overview of the Transformer-based architecture and