s with multiple magnifications of histopathology tissues, and it is useful to utilise multi- ple resolutions of the WSIs [Bejnordi et al., 2015; Toku- naga et al., 2019; Hashimoto et al., 2020; Li et al., 2021a; Zhou and Lu, 2022 ]. However, the previous works only used multiple resolutions in the same bag [Hashimoto et al., 2020 ] or concatenate the features from different resolutions together [Liet al., 2021a ]. Moreover, the two-stage training can be re- duced to an end-to-end process [Zhou and Lu, 2022 ]. Differ- ent from other works, we resemble the pathologists and make use of multiple resolutions in a hierarchical and attentive way. 3 Methodology 3.1 Problem Formulation Given the features extracted by a pre-trained neural network F∈Rn×d, where nis the number of patches in the WSI and dis the hidden dimension of the pre-trained neural network, the MIL model predicts the bag label of that WSI slide ˆYwith only the ground truth bag label Ysupervision available. The bag label Ywould be positive if and only if there is at least one positive instance in the bag, and it is defined as Eq. (1): Y=1∃i, yi= 1, 0∀i, yi= 0,(1) where yiis the ground truth label of the i-th patch. One issue with this formulation is that it cannot identify the discrim- inative instances, since each instance has the same weight under this framework. AB-MIL [Ilseet al., 2018 ]is thus a suitable solution. AB-MIL assigns attention scores to the in- stances, which reflect the importance of each instance in thefinal decision-making stage. Mathematically, assuming the hidden representation of the i-th instance is hi∈R1×dwith the corresponding attention score ai, then the bag-level rep- resentation hb∈R1×d0is calculated through Eq. (2): hb=nX i=1aihi. (2) Under the AB-MIL framework, the characteristic of WSIs having multiple resolutions is neglected. In our work, we incorporate multiple resolutions of WSIs with AB-MIL and propose the HAG-MIL framework. The HAG-MIL frame- work is designed based on AB-MIL and its motivation is that the attention scores from lower resolutions can be used as a compass to guide the model at a higher resolution. The dif- ferences between AB-MIL and our HAG-MIL framework are illustrated in Fig. 1. The inputs of the HAG-MIL framework are the features from different resolutions, and after the model at the lowest resolution has assigned attention scores to the features, the features with low attention in the higher resolu- tion are discarded in the model at a higher resolution. The process is repeated until the highest resolution is reached. 3.2 Hierarchical Attention-Guided MIL The overview of our proposed HAG-MIL framework is illus- trated in Fig. 2. Given the WSI resolutions level lto level 0, the instance representations (Fl,···,F0)extracted from multiple resolutions of any given WSI slide and the ground truth bag label Y, the HAG-MIL framework learns a map from the instance representations (Fl,···,F0)to the proba- bility distribution of the bag label (ˆpl,···,ˆp0)and the atten- tion scores of each instance (al,···,a0). Our HAG-MIL framework is defined in a recursive way. Given the instance representations (Fl,···,F0), the IATs on different levels of resolutions I={Ij|j= 0,···, l}, the HAG-MIL framework is given in Eq. (3): aj,ˆpj=  Ij␀ Fj ,ifj=l, Ij Fj d ,ifj̸=l,(3) where Fj dis the distilled features at level j, defined in Eq. (4): Fj d=Fj findtopk ids␀ aj+1, kj+1 , (4) where kj+1is the number of highest attention instances to be reserved at level j+ 1, and findtopk ids(aj+1, kj+1) first finds the indices of the instances with top-k j+1attention scores at level j+ 1and then generate the distilled indices of instances at level j, which contains exactly the same content as the instances at level j+ 1. Finding the instances in different resolutions containing exactly the same content is a bit tricky, since patching and segmenting outcomes tend to be different in different resolu- tions, especially near the borderlines. For 