 the attention scores from lower resolutions can be used as a compass to guide the model at a higher resolution. The dif- ferences between AB-MIL and our HAG-MIL framework are illustrated in Fig. 1. The inputs of the HAG-MIL framework are the features from different resolutions, and after the model at the lowest resolution has assigned attention scores to the features, the features with low attention in the higher resolu- tion are discarded in the model at a higher resolution. The process is repeated until the highest resolution is reached. 3.2 Hierarchical Attention-Guided MIL The overview of our proposed HAG-MIL framework is illus- trated in Fig. 2. Given the WSI resolutions level lto level 0, the instance representations (Fl,···,F0)extracted from multiple resolutions of any given WSI slide and the ground truth bag label Y, the HAG-MIL framework learns a map from the instance representations (Fl,···,F0)to the proba- bility distribution of the bag label (ˆpl,···,ˆp0)and the atten- tion scores of each instance (al,···,a0). Our HAG-MIL framework is defined in a recursive way. Given the instance representations (Fl,···,F0), the IATs on different levels of resolutions I={Ij|j= 0,···, l}, the HAG-MIL framework is given in Eq. (3): aj,ˆpj=  Ij␀ Fj ,ifj=l, Ij Fj d ,ifj̸=l,(3) where Fj dis the distilled features at level j, defined in Eq. (4): Fj d=Fj findtopk ids␀ aj+1, kj+1 , (4) where kj+1is the number of highest attention instances to be reserved at level j+ 1, and findtopk ids(aj+1, kj+1) first finds the indices of the instances with top- kj+1attention scores at level j+ 1and then generate the distilled indices of instances at level j, which contains exactly the same content as the instances at level j+ 1. Finding the instances in different resolutions containing exactly the same content is a bit tricky, since patching and segmenting outcomes tend to be different in different resolu- tions, especially near the borderlines. For example, as shown in Fig. 2, pat