ancers. Conclusions Our findings demonstrate that samples from GTEx can serve as reference normal samples for cancers, especially those do not have available adjacent tissue samples. A deep-learning based approach holds promise to select proper normal samples. Similar content being viewed by others A comparison of RNA-Seq data preprocessing pipelines for transcriptomic predictions across independent studies Article Open access 08 May 2024 CancerNet: a unified deep learning network for pan-cancer diagnostics Article Open access 13 June 2022 Unifying cancer and normal RNA sequencing data from different sources Article Open access 17 April 2018 Explore related subjects Discover the latest articles, books and news in related subjects, suggested using machine learning. Cancer Models Molecular Target Validation Next-generation sequencing RNA sequencing Targeted resequencing Tumour Heterogeneity Gene Expression Analysis in Cancer Genomics Background Comparing molecular profiles of disease tissue samples and normal tissue samples is often employed to identify a signature of the disease. The signature defined as differentially expressed genes between two groups is critical to understanding abnormal disease features and guiding therapeutic discovery [ 1 , 2 , 3 , 4 , 5 , 6 ]. For example, a gene expression signature created from the comparison of liver cancer tumor samples and adjacent tissue samples was used to discover anti-parasite drugs as therapeutics for liver cancer [ 7 ]. Analysis of matched tumor and normal profiles identified common transcriptional and epigenetic signals shared across cancer types [ 8 ]. Large-scale integrative analysis of cancer pr mples for every cancer or cancer subtype. The recent GTEx project has profiled samples from healthy individuals, providing an excellent resource for this field, yet the feasibility of using GTEx samples as the reference remains unanswered. We analyze RNA-Seq data processed from the same computational pipeline and systema